<paper id="1971842242"><title>An O ( n log log n )-time algorithm for triangulating a simple polygon</title><year>1988</year><authors><author org="Princeton Univ., Princeton, NJ" id="350567680">Robert E. Tarjan</author><author org="Princeton Univ., Princeton, NJ" id="2486707307">Christopher van Wyk</author></authors><n_citation>133</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>6840519</reference><reference>1967635159</reference><reference>1983487792</reference><reference>2010483698</reference><reference>2023182928</reference><reference>2037007500</reference><reference>2041437464</reference><reference>2051831392</reference><reference>2069750902</reference><reference>2073058919</reference><reference>2077180154</reference><reference>2085041675</reference><reference>2088864905</reference><reference>2130055503</reference><reference>2132026455</reference><reference>2169271351</reference></references><venue id="153560523" type="J">SIAM Journal on Computing</venue><doi>10.1137/0217010</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.52662">Diagonal</keyword><keyword weight="0.45329">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.45927">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.6069">Polygon</keyword><keyword weight="0.67222">Polygon covering</keyword><keyword weight="0.4163">Algorithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.62109">Pick's theorem</keyword><keyword weight="0.66171">Simple polygon</keyword><keyword weight="0.60447">Star-shaped polygon</keyword><keyword weight="0.39962">Mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.6816">Polygon triangulation</keyword><keyword weight="0.63">Monotone polygon</keyword></keywords><publisher>Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics</publisher><abstract>Given a simple n-vertex polygon, the triangulation problem is to partition the interior of the polygon into $n - 2$ triangles by adding $n - 3$ nonintersecting diagonals. We propose an $O(n\log \log n)$-time algorithm for this problem, improving on the previously best bound of $O(n\log n)$ and showing that triangulation is not as hard as sorting. Improved algorithms for several other computational geometry problems, including testing whether a polygon is simple, follow from our result.</abstract></paper>